title: Re-searched the vault and left it in CON
PMPS faulted again from random change in the reported photon energy
text: This caused a bit of downtime. MEC called us since the PMPS was preventing beam. Nothing changed on our end which would have generated the fault. We got a request from Sebastian Boutet to acknowledge the faults. The PMPS has a calculator for the photon energy that watches PVs on the accelerator side. Either the calculator has spontaneous miscalculations, or one of the input PVs jumps spontaneously. Generating another CATER for this recurring issue. These situations are unfortunate because neither side wants to acknowledge the fault, because neither side believes they are the ones that generated the fault.

title: Gun dropouts
text: Modulator looks fine, I think, but no RF amplitude intermittently. Trying to get a BSA data set during the dropouts...

title: * Re: Gun dropouts
text: This seems to have settled down and stopped happening. Could have been simply some fast MPS fault which cleared right away... Did see a couple MPS PIC trips IN20 425...which sounds more like response to gun trips than causing them.

title: First Walkthrough Complete - no problems found
DL2 energy single pulse dropouts...hard to find source.
text: RTBSA is the go-to tool for this, but we were not successful at finding the source using that tool. Matt did find 28-8 had some ugly FTPs, so focused on that station. From the BV FTPs it is clear that the MOD is not pulsing with stability. Nudged thyratron reservoir up a touch from 3.95V to 4.0V seems to have helped that station, but now there is another station causing dropouts too...need to chase down and find that one.

title: * Re: DL2 energy single pulse dropouts...hard to find source.
text: Went through all L3 stations looking at plots like this. Note the wibble at t=2.5 seconds I think is a FTP happening...not of interest. None of the stations' BSA readout gave any indication of correlating with these DL2 energy dropouts.

title: Took 28-8 off the beam
text: This station was continuing to cause problems so we took it off and LEM'd. This station is also being used for the MFX delivery during day shift, which is something we should be wary of during the switchover. It already has an open CATER: 154808

title: * Re: DL2 energy single pulse dropouts...hard to find source.
text: Got the dropouts to go away. We starting deacting L3 stations one at a time until the dropouts stopped. The dropouts stopped when we deactivated 28-6. BSA tools were not showing this to us since the PAD is reading "NaN"s for the phase (but it does not show camac faults on the CUD). Beam volts and AMPL FTPs look healthy at standby time.

title: * Re: DL2 energy single pulse dropouts...hard to find source.
text: Got the dropouts to go away. We starting deacting L3 stations one at a time until the dropouts stopped. The dropouts stopped when we deactivated 28-6. BSA tools were not showing this to us since the PAD is reading "NaN"s for the phase (but it does not show camac faults on the CUD). Beam volts and AMPL FTPs look healthy at standby time. Tried IPL PIOP, and now both PHAS and AMPL are "NaN"...and the beam dropouts persist when the station is assigned.

title: 28-6 and 28-8 both have dropout/jitter issues which will make them undesirable for high energy MFX running today.
text: 28-6 the dropouts are mysterious. FTPs don't show any sign of a problem, but the beam sure drops out a lot when this station is assigned. Also, the PAD PHAS and AMPL are "NaN" which does not resolve with PIOP IPL. It has CATER about the PAD AMPL and PHAS being NaN. 28-8 the modulator pulse can clearly be seen moving around on FTPs, as if thyratron needs ranging. Tried moving thyratron reservoir a bit...did not help so put that back. It has CATER for BV jitters.

title: Lost beam for a couple minutes
text: We were suddenly losing beam in BC2 with no indication of what went wrong, but the L2 actuators were railed negative. Fixing the 6x6 with values from 10 minutes ago restored beam and it looks fine now.

text: Discussed the next steps for the BL 12-1 problem. Needed relays for replacement in suspect chassis might not arrive promptly. Swapping in a new chassis is next likely step.
